Persimmon is a really nice restaurant with really good food. Will any of the combinations surprise or wow you? Probably not. But, everything is prepared really well and everything tastes good. The portobello and blue cheese ravioli are delicious (could have had another portion). The duck is cooked perfectly and is very tasty. The crab cakes are very good and the sauce is just scrumptious. The molten chocolate cake and the apple crisp are both solid desserts. A lovely glass of Barbera and a strong but tasty cocktail accompanied our meals well.  Service was quick and friendly. Outdoor seating is available and it was fun to people watch, though Wisconsin Ave. is by no means picturesque. There is a public parking lot nearby.

Wonderful service. The managers/owners are always hand on from taking orders, clearing tables, to regularly check on patrons, on top of their regular duties despite the ample number of staff. Easy to see their passion and love of their jobs in their meticulous arrangement of the bar shelves or their keeping your water glass always full. As appetizer, wasabi oyster is a delight: A salty crunchy coating, an expectedly tart soy sauce and julienne cucumber compose a symphony of taste and texture. Seared scallop is simply delicious but the lone scallop makes the dish sad. Tuna tartare is great. Antipasto board is very satisfying. For entrees, bouillabaisse is marvelous even though saffron and table ground pepper might make it even better. Crab cake is on par with the best in Maryland. Lobster roll is a miss, too banal, too small. Dessert offers a sublime hot lava cake topped with cold ice cream, a creme brûlée that make you want to lick the dish clean. The intriguing menu beckons you to come back again and again until you have tried all the items.

We tried Persimmon during restaurant week and didn’t have the problems some people mentioned. Menu is very large and plenty to choose from. Dinner: scallops and risotto too salty, branzino with gnocchi where just ok . It could have been other type of fried fish and the gnocchi!?! Where hard to find. The lobster roll was the best but I would not pay the original price of $24 for it. Dessert: cream brûlée was very good and the molted cake as well. Servers need training in how to serve and politeness. Overall a 3,5 rating.

We had a party of eight for Mother's day and 7 out of the 8 chose sunset special.   The food was good for the most part.  The portion size was ok except for the hanger steak which alone is  $28 and sunset special is $33 which includes appetizer and dessert.  This is where it loses at least one star.   First hanger steak is a cheaper cut of beef and it came with about seven slices of beef roughly  3 inch by .5 inch thick.  For $28 dollars you would think they would give you a bigger portion.  Then comes the dessert.  I ordered trio mini  cream puffs.  Here is where it goes continues downhill.  The normal cream puff order comes with 3 mini cream puffs which is about 2 inch in diameter.  I pointed to the server that it had only two and menu stated trio.   A lady came by maybe the manager??? and explained that sunset special you only get two.   First the dessert is nothing more than flour for most part.   How much more would it cost them to throw in the third one, maybe .50  in materials????  How cheap can Persimmon be????  Here it loses another star.  My advice IF YOU MUST GO TO PERSIMMON, STAY AWAY FROM HANGER STEAK AND DON"T ORDER CREAM PUFF FOR DESSERT if you choose to go the sunset route.

The food here is great, and the service is really friendly. We have been back several times, now, and we have yet to have any appetizer or main dish that hasn't been fabulous. The early bird dinners are one of the best deals going in town. On the downside: desserts are not so great, sadly--we haven't liked any of ours. Also, the noise from the kitchen is quite obtrusive and the room is small, so there is no place to sit to get away from it. It spoils the warm, intimate atmosphere. However, the food at these prices is worth it anyways.
